From: Nick Cao <nickcao@nichi.co>
Date: Wed, 18 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] nest/iface: preserve VRF master in if_delete() to fix async
 notification race

if_delete() creates a zeroed struct iface with only name and IF_SHUTDOWN
set, then passes it to if_update_locked(). Since the zeroed struct has
master=NULL, if_update_locked() sets it to &default_vrf at line 468.

When if_update_locked() processes the deletion via the IF_CHANGE_TOO_MUCH
branch, it:

  1. Calls if_change_flags() which enqueues an async IF_CHANGE_DOWN
     notification (or one was already pending from an earlier
     RTM_NEWLINK admin-down event), holding a pointer to the iface
     struct.
  2. Calls memcpy(i, new, sizeof(*i)) which overwrites the iface
     struct in-place, including i->master which becomes &default_vrf.

When the Babel (or any VRF-bound) protocol thread later processes the
queued notification, if_send_notify() checks if_in_vrf(i, p->vrf). Since
i->master is now &default_vrf instead of the original VRF, the check
fails and the notification is silently dropped. The protocol never learns
the interface was deleted.

The consequence is that the protocol keeps a zombie reference to the
deleted interface. For Babel, this means the hello timer keeps firing
and sendmsg() fails with ENODEV on every tick, producing an unbounded
stream of "Socket error on <iface>: No such device" errors.

With a small number of interfaces, this race is unlikely because the
protocol thread typically drains the notification queue fast enough. But
when many VRF interfaces are deleted in bulk (e.g., IPsec XFRM tunnels
torn down by strongSwan), the netlink handler processes RTM_NEWLINK and
RTM_DELLINK events faster than the protocol thread can drain them. The
memcpy from a later RTM_DELLINK overwrites i->master while the DOWN
notification from an earlier RTM_NEWLINK is still queued, corrupting it.

In production with ~700 XFRM interfaces in a Babel mesh over IPsec, this
results in hundreds of zombie interfaces generating ~180K errors/hour.

Fix by preserving the original master and master_index in the zeroed
struct passed to if_update_locked(). This ensures that after the memcpy,
i->master still points to the correct VRF, and queued notifications pass
the if_in_vrf() check regardless of timing.

This bug is specific to BIRD v3's async notification model; BIRD v2 used
synchronous notification delivery and was not affected.

Signed-off-by: Nick Cao <nickcao@nichi.co>
---
 nest/iface.c | 2 ++
 1 file changed, 2 insertions(+)

diff --git a/nest/iface.c b/nest/iface.c
index 00217b3..33603ca 100644
--- a/nest/iface.c
+++ b/nest/iface.c
@@ -430,6 +430,8 @@ if_delete(struct iface *old)
   struct iface f = {};
   strncpy(f.name, old->name, sizeof(f.name)-1);
   f.flags = IF_SHUTDOWN;
+  f.master = old->master;
+  f.master_index = old->master_index;
   if_update_locked(&f);
   IFACE_UNLOCK;
 }
